Under COBS 14.1.1(1), the trustee or operator of a stakeholder pension scheme is treated as a 'retail client' for the purposes of COBS 14. Additionally, under COBS 14.1.1(2), 'sell' includes 'sell, personally recommend or arrange the sale of' in relation to a designated investment. This means that the firm's personal recommendation of the stakeholder pension scheme falls within the scope of 'selling' under COBS 14, and the client is classified as a retail client for these purposes.

Since the client is a retail customer who has suffered foreseeable harm but has not made a complaint, PRIN 2A.10.2R(2) applies. The firm must follow the modified DISP rules, specifically DISP 1.4.1R as modified, which requires the firm to:

1. Investigate the circumstances which led to the foreseeable harm competently, diligently and impartially, obtaining additional information as necessary;
2. Assess fairly, consistently and promptly: (a) the subject matter of the foreseeable harm, (c) what remedial action or redress (or both) may be appropriate, and (d) if appropriate, whether another firm may be solely or jointly responsible;
3. Offer redress or remedial action when it decides this is appropriate;
4. Explain to the retail customer promptly and in a way that is fair, clear and not misleading that harm has been identified, its assessment of the harm, its decision as to what action is appropriate, and that the customer has a right to make a complaint if not satisfied;
5. Comply promptly with any offer of remedial action or redress accepted by the retail customer.

Under PRIN 2A.10.2R(2)(d) (modified DISP 1.4.2G), relevant factors in the assessment include all available evidence, similarities with other complaints or instances of harm, relevant FCA guidance, and analysis of Financial Ombudsman Service decisions concerning similar fact patterns.

The firm faces obligations under both BCOBS 5.1 and PRIN 2A.10.

**Under BCOBS 5.1.3B**, since it has become apparent after exercising the right of set-off that the firm set off debts against consumers' subsistence balances, the firm should refund to each consumer the sum debited from their account unless it is fair not to do so (BCOBS 5.1.3B(1)). If the firm decides not to provide a refund in any case, it must be able to justify that it is fair not to do so and should consider taking other remedial action having regard to BCOBS 5.1.1R and Principle 6 (BCOBS 5.1.3B(2)). The firm must also ensure its ongoing service remains prompt, efficient and fair under BCOBS 5.1.1R.

**Under PRIN 2A.10**, since the firm has identified foreseeable harm caused to retail customers but no complaints have been received, it must follow the modified DISP procedures set out in PRIN 2A.10.2R(2). Specifically, per the modified DISP 1.4.1R, the firm must:
1. Investigate the circumstances which led to the foreseeable harm competently, diligently and impartially, obtaining additional information as necessary;
2. Assess fairly, consistently and promptly the subject matter of the harm, what remedial action or redress may be appropriate, and whether another firm may be jointly responsible;
3. Offer redress or remedial action when it decides this is appropriate;
4. Explain to each affected retail customer promptly and in a fair, clear and not misleading way that harm has been identified, its assessment of the harm, its decision on appropriate action, and that the customer has a right to make a complaint if not satisfied;
5. Comply promptly with any offer of remedial action or redress accepted by the customer.

Additionally, under PRIN 2A.10.2R(2)(d) (modified DISP 1.4.2G), the firm should consider factors including all available evidence, similarities with complaints received, relevant FCA guidance, and analysis of Financial Ombudsman Service decisions on similar fact patterns.

In practice, the firm must both provide the BCOBS-required refunds of subsistence balances and follow the PRIN 2A.10 proactive redress process to investigate, assess, and communicate with all 200 affected customers—even though no complaints have been made.
